The '''Long-Range Hypersonic Weapon''' ('''LRHW'''), also known as the '''Dark Eagle,'''<ref name=":2" /> is an [[intermediate-range ballistic missile|intermediate-range]] [[surface-to-surface missile|surface-to-surface]] [[boost-glide]] [[hypersonic weapon]] being developed for use by the [[United States Army]]. The [[United States Navy]] intends to procure a ship/submarine-launched variant of the missile as part of the service's '''Intermediate-Range Conventional Prompt Strike''' ('''IRCPS''') program.<ref name=lrhwRange /> The weapon consists of a large [[Booster (rocketry)|rocket booster]] that carries the unpowered Common-Hypersonic Glide Body (C-HGB) in a [[nose cone]]. Once the booster reaches significant altitude and speed, it releases the C-HGB, which glides at [[Hypersonic speed|hypersonic speeds]] as it descends towards its target. [[Dynetics]] will build the [[hypersonic glide vehicle]], while [[Lockheed Martin]] will build the booster as well as assemble the missile and launch equipment.<ref>{{cite web |last=Roblin |first=Sebastien |date=30 April 2020 |title=The Pentagon Plans to Deploy an Arsenal of Hypersonic Weapons in the 2020s |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/sebastienroblin/2020/04/30/the-pentagons-plans-to-deploy-an-arsenal-of-hypersonic-weapons-in-the-2020s/?sh=405b983a3a5d |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231020012726/https://www.forbes.com/sites/sebastienroblin/2020/04/30/the-pentagons-plans-to-deploy-an-arsenal-of-hypersonic-weapons-in-the-2020s/?sh=405b983a3a5d |archive-date=20 October 2023 |access-date=15 May 2021 |work=Forbes}}</ref><ref>https://www.congress.gov/crs-product/IF11991</ref>

The C-HGB has been successfully tested in October 2017, March 2020,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=20 March 2020 |title=Hypersonics: Army, Navy Test Common Glide Body |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2020/03/hypersonics-army-navy-test-common-glide-body/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230325022305/https://breakingdefense.com/2020/03/hypersonics-army-navy-test-common-glide-body/ |archive-date=25 March 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=20 March 2020 |title=Department of Defense tests hypersonic glide body |url=https://www.army.mil/article/233873/department_of_defense_tests_hypersonic_glide_body |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230417075617/https://www.army.mil/article/233873/department_of_defense_tests_hypersonic_glide_body |archive-date=17 April 2023 |website=U.S. Army}}</ref>  28 June 2024,<ref name=lrhwCpsSuccTest /> and 12 December 2024.<ref name="capeCanavAur">{{Cite press release|title=Army and Navy Successfully Test Conventional Hypersonic Missile |url=https://www.war.gov/News/Releases/Release/Article/3999835/army-and-navy-successfully-test-conventional-hypersonic-missile/ |date=2024-12-12|website=U.S. Department of Defense |language=en-US}}</ref> The missile had been planned to enter service with the Army in 2023.<ref name= lrhw2023 /> The Navy intends to field the weapon aboard its [[Zumwalt-class destroyer|''Zumwalt''-class destroyers]] by 2025<ref name= lrhw2023 >Megan Eckstein [https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2023/02/18/navy-awards-lockheed-martin-12b-contract-for-hypersonic-missiles/ (17 Feb 2023) Navy awards Lockheed Martin $1.2B contract for hypersonic missiles]</ref> and later on its Block V [[Virginia-class submarine|''Virginia''-class submarines]]<ref>{{cite web |publisher=USNI News |date=28 April 2021 |access-date=15 May 2021 |title=CNO: Hypersonic Weapons at Sea to Premiere on Zumwalt Destroyers in 2025 |first=Sam |last=LaGrone |url=https://news.usni.org/2021/04/28/cno-hypersonic-weapons-at-sea-to-premiere-on-zumwalt-destroyers-in-2025}}</ref> in 2028; it was intended to also be fielded on guided missile variants of the [[Ohio-class submarine|''Ohio''-class ballistic missile submarines]], but funding delays and the boats' impending retirement caused those plans to be scrapped.<ref>[https://news.usni.org/2021/11/18/hypersonic-weapons-on-track-to-deploy-on-attack-submarines-in-2028 Hypersonic Weapons on Track to Deploy on Attack Submarines in 2028]. ''[[USNI News]]''. 18 November 2021.</ref>

==Development and testing==
===Common-Hypersonic Glide Body===
In 2018, the [[United States Navy|Navy]] was designated to lead the design of the Common-Hypersonic Glide Body with input from the Army's Rapid Capabilities and Critical Technologies Office.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Thurgood |first=Neil |date=4 September 2019 |title=Hypersonics by 2023 |url=https://www.army.mil/article/226678/hypersonics_by_2023 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230905225500/https://www.army.mil/article/226678/hypersonics_by_2023 |archive-date=5 September 2023 |access-date=15 May 2021 |website=U.S. Army}}</ref>

====Design====
[[File:LRHW_on_Transporter_Erector_Launcher,_Nellis_AFB.png|thumb|LRHW on [[transporter erector launcher]], 3 August 2024, Exercise Bamboo Eagle 24-3, Nellis AFB<ref>{{cite web | title=US Army's Long-Range Hypersonic Weapon Battery integrates in Exercise Bamboo Eagle|first=Ryan|last=DeBooy|publisher=US Army| date=30 August 2024 | url=https://www.army.mil/article/279357/us_armys_long_range_hypersonic_weapon_battery_integrates_in_exercise_bamboo_eagle}}</ref>]]

[[File:US DoD, Navy, Army jointly conducted a flight experiment of a common hypersonic glide body from Pacific Missile Range Facility, Hawaii on 19 March 2020.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|A 2020 test launch of a [[UGM-27 Polaris|STARS booster]] carrying a prototype of the Common-Hypersonic Glide Body]]
The design of the Common-Hypersonic Glide Body with a kinetic energy projectile warhead<ref name=hascWeberRumford >House Armed Services Committee (12 Mar 2024) [https://armedservices.house.gov/sites/evo-subsites/republicans-armedservices.house.gov/files/03.12.24%20Weber%20-%20Rumford%20Statement.pdf Weber-Rumford Statement]</ref> is based on the previously developed Alternate Re-Entry System, which was tested in the early 2010s as part of the Army's Advanced Hypersonic Weapon program.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sayler |first=Kelley M. |date=11 July 2019 |title=Hypersonic Weapons: Background and Issues for Congress |url=https://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/6189872/Hypersonic-Weapons-Background-and-Issues-for.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231010153518/https://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/6189872/Hypersonic-Weapons-Background-and-Issues-for.pdf |archive-date=10 October 2023 |website=Congressional Research Service}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Sayler |first=Kelley M. |date=13 February 2023 |title=Hypersonic Weapons: Background and Issues for Congress |url=https://sgp.fas.org/crs/weapons/R45811.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106095948/https://sgp.fas.org/crs/weapons/R45811.pdf |archive-date=6 January 2024 |website=Congressional Research Service}}</ref> The Alternate Re-Entry System was itself based on the Sandia Winged Energetic Reentry Vehicle Experiment (SWERVE) prototype developed by [[Sandia National Laboratories]] in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web |last=Threvithick |first=Joseph |date=3 June 2019 |title=Here's What The Army's First Ever Operational Hypersonic Missile Unit Will Look Like |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/28340/heres-what-the-armys-first-ever-operational-hypersonic-missile-unit-will-look-like |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231020013309/https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/28340/heres-what-the-armys-first-ever-operational-hypersonic-missile-unit-will-look-like |archive-date=20 October 2023 |access-date=15 May 2021 |website=The Drive}}</ref> Design work is by Sandia, while [[Dynetics]] constructs prototypes and test units.

====Testing====
The first test of the Intermediate Range Conventional Prompt Strike Flight Experiment-1, was on 30 October 2017. A missile capable of fitting in the launch tube of an [[Ohio-class submarine|''Ohio''-class ballistic missile submarine]] flew over 2,000 nautical miles from Hawaii to the Marshall Islands at hypersonic speeds.<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 January 2019 |title=Conventional Prompt Global Strike and Long-Range Ballistic Missiles: Background and Issues |url=https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R41464/45 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220416145603/https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R41464/45 |archive-date=16 April 2022 |access-date=15 May 2021 |website=Congressional Research Service}}</ref> The Common-Hypersonic Glide Body was tested in March 2020.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> LRHW subsystems were tested at Project Convergence 2022 (PC22).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tucker |first=Patrick |date=21 October 2022 |title=The Military's Network Warfare Experiment Scaled Up This Year |url=https://www.defenseone.com/technology/2022/10/militarys-network-warfare-experiment-scaled-year/378790/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231009174141/https://www.defenseone.com/technology/2022/10/militarys-network-warfare-experiment-scaled-year/378790/ |archive-date=9 October 2023 |website=Defense One}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Eckstein |first=Megan |date=2 November 2022 |title=US Navy touts hypersonic missile progress ahead of 2025 fielding |url=https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2022/11/02/us-navy-touts-hypersonic-missile-progress-ahead-of-2025-fielding/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240109013517/https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2022/11/02/us-navy-touts-hypersonic-missile-progress-ahead-of-2025-fielding/ |archive-date=9 January 2024 |website=Defense News}}</ref>

On 28 June 2024, the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] announced a successful recent end-to-end test of the US Army's Long-Range Hypersonic Weapon all-up round (AUR) and the US Navy's Conventional Prompt Strike. The missile was launched from the [[Pacific Missile Range Facility]], Kauai, Hawaii,<ref name=lrhwCpsSuccTest> [https://www.war.gov/News/Releases/Release/Article/3821376/dod-completes-flight-test-of-hypersonic-missile/ (28 Jun 2024) "DOD Completes Flight Test of Hypersonic Missile"] US Department of Defense</ref> landing more than 2000 miles away in the [[Marshall Islands]].<ref name= 2Jul2024Update>Andrew Feickert, Congressional Research Service [https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/IF/IF11991 (updated 2 Jul 2024) "The U.S. Army’s Long-Range Hypersonic Weapon (LRHW):Dark Eagle"] Report IF11991</ref> A second 2024 test of the land-based launcher<ref name=oneMoreTest>Judson, Jen. [https://www.armytimes.com/land/2024/09/06/us-army-aiming-for-one-more-hypersonic-weapon-test-by-years-end/ (6 Sep 2024) "US Army aiming for one more hypersonic weapon test by year’s end"] </ref> fired an all-up round (AUR) from a transporter erector launcher (TEL) using a Battery Operations Center at Cape Canaveral on 12 December 2024, which was successful.<ref name=capeCanavAur/>

===Boosters===
The first stage solid rocket motor was tested on 27 May 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Eckstein |first=Megan |date=27 May 2021 |title=US Navy conducts first live-fire test of hypersonic missile motor |url=https://www.defensenews.com/training-sim/2021/05/27/us-navy-conducts-first-live-fire-test-of-hypersonic-missile-motor/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210601165518/https://www.defensenews.com/training-sim/2021/05/27/us-navy-conducts-first-live-fire-test-of-hypersonic-missile-motor/ |archive-date=1 June 2021 |website=Defense News}}</ref>

Both stages of the missile booster as well as a thrust vector control system were tested in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Katz |first=Justin |date=26 August 2021 |title=Navy Successfully Tests Solid Rocket Motor For Hypersonic Weapon |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2021/08/navy-successfully-tests-solid-rocket-motor-for-cps/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106050803/https://breakingdefense.com/2021/08/navy-successfully-tests-solid-rocket-motor-for-cps/ |archive-date=6 January 2024 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Judson |first=Jen |date=26 August 2021 |title=US Navy tests second-stage rocket motor for hypersonic weapon |url=https://www.defensenews.com/training-sim/2021/08/26/us-navy-tests-second-stage-rocket-motor-for-hypersonic-weapon/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210829154734/https://www.defensenews.com/training-sim/2021/08/26/us-navy-tests-second-stage-rocket-motor-for-hypersonic-weapon/ |archive-date=29 August 2021 |website=Defense News}}</ref>

On 29 October 2021, the booster rocket for the Long-Range Hypersonic Weapon was successfully tested in a static test in [[Utah]]; the first stage thrust vector control system was included in the test.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Stone |first=Mike |date=29 October 2021 |title=U.S. successfully tests hypersonic booster motor in Utah |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-successfully-tests-hypersonic-booster-motor-utah-2021-10-29/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211029161109/https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-successfully-tests-hypersonic-booster-motor-utah-2021-10-29/ |archive-date=29 October 2021 |website=Reuters}}</ref>

In March 2021, training with inert missile canisters began.<ref name="auto"/> On 7 October 2021, [[17th Field Artillery Brigade (United States)|17th Field Artillery Brigade]] of the [[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]] received ground equipment for the first operational LRHW battery.<ref>{{cite web |date=7 October 2021 |title=Army delivers first hypersonics ground equipment |url=https://www.army.mil/article/250991/army_delivers_first_hypersonics_ground_equipment |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231020022203/https://www.army.mil/article/250991/army_delivers_first_hypersonics_ground_equipment |archive-date=20 October 2023 |access-date=17 October 2021 |website=U.S. Army}}</ref>

In June 2022 in Hawaii, a launch failure of Conventional Prompt Strike occurred after ignition.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Herskovitz |first1=Jon |last2=Capaccio |first2=Tony |date=29 June 2022 |title=Hypersonic missile test fails off Hawaii in fresh setback for program |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2022/06/29/breaking-news/hypersonic-missile-test-fails-off-hawaii-in-fresh-setback-for-program/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231020013250/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2022/06/29/breaking-news/hypersonic-missile-test-fails-off-hawaii-in-fresh-setback-for-program/ |archive-date=20 October 2023 |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |agency=Bloomberg News}}</ref> The test of a completely assembled CPS weapon, which uses a two-stage booster,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cole |first=Brendan |date=1 July 2022 |title=Russia Reacts to U.S. Hypersonic Missile Failure |url=https://www.newsweek.com/russia-reacts-us-hypersonic-missile-failure-pentagon-chgb-test-1721004 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231020022203/https://www.newsweek.com/russia-reacts-us-hypersonic-missile-failure-pentagon-chgb-test-1721004 |archive-date=20 October 2023 |website=Newsweek}}</ref> failed before ignition of the C-HGB.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Liebermann |first=Oren |date=30 June 2022 |title=Latest US hypersonic test fails after 'anomaly' during first full flight test |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2022/06/30/politics/us-hypersonic-missile-test-fails/index.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231024164806/https://edition.cnn.com/2022/06/30/politics/us-hypersonic-missile-test-fails/index.html |archive-date=24 October 2023 |access-date=9 January 2024 |website=CNN}}</ref> Conventional Prompt Strike was successfully tested 12 December 2024.<ref name=capeCanavAur/>

==Entry into service==
[[File:Emplacement of pod on long-range hypersonic weapon transporter erector launcher.jpg|thumb|LRHW placed on [[transporter erector launcher]]]]
The [[United States Army]] intends to deploy the Long-Range Hypersonic Weapon in an eight missile [[Artillery battery#Modern battery organization|battery]] containing four [[Heavy Expanded Mobility Tactical Truck|M983]] trucks and trailers each holding two missiles in launch canisters alongside a command vehicle.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> The LRHW has been also named ''Dark Eagle'' by the US Army.<ref name="darkEagle">{{Cite web |last=Hitchens |first=Theresa |date=11 August 2021 |title='Confident' Of 2023 Fielding Goal, Army Dubs Hypersonic Weapon 'Dark Eagle' |url=https://breakingdefense.sites.breakingmedia.com/2021/08/confident-of-2023-fielding-goal-army-dubs-hypersonic-weapon-dark-eagle/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231005155113/https://breakingdefense.com/2021/08/confident-of-2023-fielding-goal-army-dubs-hypersonic-weapon-dark-eagle/ |archive-date=5 October 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Rogoway |first=Tyler |date=5 March 2023 |title=Mysterious Launch Out Of Cape Canaveral Appears Imminent (Updated) |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/mysterious-launch-out-of-cape-canaveral-appears-imminent |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230912223758/https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/mysterious-launch-out-of-cape-canaveral-appears-imminent |archive-date=12 September 2023 |website=The Drive}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Kelly |first=Emre |date=6 March 2023 |title=Department of Defense scrubs hypersonic missile test at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station |url=https://eu.floridatoday.com/story/tech/science/space/2023/03/06/dod-scrubs-hypersonic-missile-test-at-cape-canaveral-space-force-station/69976353007/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230326213118/https://eu.floridatoday.com/story/tech/science/space/2023/03/06/dod-scrubs-hypersonic-missile-test-at-cape-canaveral-space-force-station/69976353007/ |archive-date=26 March 2023 |website=Florida Today}}</ref>

In February 2023, the 5th Battalion, [[3rd Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|3rd Field Artillery Regiment]] (5-3 LRFB)—1st MDTF's long-range fires battalion—deployed the LRHW from [[Joint Base Lewis–McChord|Joint Base Lewis-McChord]], [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] to [[Cape Canaveral Space Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Florida]]. The first battery of missiles was expected to be deployed by end of September 2023.<ref name="5,3Lrfb">{{cite web |last=Parlato |first=Richard |date=30 March 2023 |title=1st Multi-Domain Task Force Deploys the Army's First Long-Range Hypersonic Weapon System |url=https://www.army.mil/article/265349/1st_multi_domain_task_force_deploys_the_armys_first_long_range_hypersonic_weapon_system |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231203182256/https://www.army.mil/article/265349/1st_multi_domain_task_force_deploys_the_armys_first_long_range_hypersonic_weapon_system |archive-date=3 December 2023 |accessdate=16 September 2023 |website=U.S. Army}}</ref>

On 7 September 2023, a test launch of the LRHW system was canceled due to an unspecified failure of pre-flight checks.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Capaccio |first=Anthony |date=7 September 2023 |title=US Army cancels flight test of Long Range Hypersonic Weapon |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-09-07/us-army-cancels-flight-test-of-long-range-hypersonic-weapon#xj4y7vzkg |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230907145948/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-09-07/us-army-cancels-flight-test-of-long-range-hypersonic-weapon?leadSource=uverify%20wall |archive-date=7 September 2023 |accessdate=8 September 2023 |website=Bloomberg |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Capaccio |first=Anthony |date=14 September 2023 |title=US Army Faces Facts: Its Hypersonic Weapon To Miss a Deadline |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-09-14/us-army-faces-facts-its-hypersonic-weapon-will-miss-a-deadline |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230914214958/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-09-14/us-army-faces-facts-its-hypersonic-weapon-will-miss-a-deadline |archive-date=14 September 2023 |website=Bloomberg}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Weinberger |first=Sharon |date=18 September 2023 |title=Hypersonic Missiles Are Game-Changers, and America Doesn't Have Them |url=https://www.wsj.com/politics/national-security/hypersonic-missiles-america-military-behind-936a3128 |url-access=subscription |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20231027014639/https://www.wsj.com/politics/national-security/hypersonic-missiles-america-military-behind-936a3128 |archive-date=27 October 2023 |website=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> [[United States Assistant Secretary of the Army for Acquisition, Logistics, and Technology]] Douglas R. Bush revealed that the launcher had a "mechanical engineering problem", and that a new plan was in place to correct and test it.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Roque |first=Ashley |date=3 December 2023 |title=Army has a revised hypersonic test plan to address launcher 'problem': Official |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2023/12/army-has-a-revised-hypersonic-test-plan-to-address-launcher-problem-official/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231227211023/https://breakingdefense.com/2023/12/army-has-a-revised-hypersonic-test-plan-to-address-launcher-problem-official/ |archive-date=27 December 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Harper |first=Jon |date=7 November 2023 |title=Army anticipates another delay in fielding Dark Eagle hypersonic weapon after detecting 'problem' |url=https://defensescoop.com/2023/11/07/army-expects-another-delay-in-fielding-dark-eagle-hypersonic-weapon-after-detecting-problem/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231216094210/https://defensescoop.com/2023/11/07/army-expects-another-delay-in-fielding-dark-eagle-hypersonic-weapon-after-detecting-problem/ |archive-date=16 December 2023 |website=DefenseScoop}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Harper |first=Jon |date=3 December 2023 |title=Army hopes to field Dark Eagle hypersonic missile in summer 2024 after resolving problems with launcher |url=https://defensescoop.com/2023/12/03/army-hopes-to-field-dark-eagle-hypersonic-missile-in-summer-2024-after-resolving-problems-with-launcher/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231216094210/https://defensescoop.com/2023/12/03/army-hopes-to-field-dark-eagle-hypersonic-missile-in-summer-2024-after-resolving-problems-with-launcher/ |archive-date=16 December 2023 |website=DefenseScoop}}</ref> An LRHW all-up round was successfully tested sometime prior to 28 June 2024.<ref name=lrhwCpsSuccTest />

On 12 December 2024, the Army and the Navy announced that the Dark Eagle had completed a successful end-to-end [[flight test]] at [[Cape Canaveral Space Launch Complex 46|Space Launch Complex 46]] at Cape Canaveral.<ref name="capeCanavAur" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Easley |first=Mikala |date=2024-12-13 |title=Army, Navy complete highly anticipated hypersonic missile test |url=https://defensescoop.com/2024/12/13/army-navy-second-hypersonic-missile-test-2024-aur-lrhw-dark-eagle-cps/ |access-date=2024-12-14 |website=DefenseScoop |language=en-US}}</ref>

On 29 April 2026, the [[US Central Command]] requested that the Dark Eagle be sent to the Middle East for potential deployment against Iran during the [[2026 Iran war]], marking the first time Washington would deploy the technology, according to [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]. According to a person with direct knowledge of the issue, US CENTCOM made the request after Iran moved its missile launchers out of range of the US Army's [[Precision Strike Missile]], the current technology it has deployed.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-04-29  |title=US Seeks to Deploy Hypersonic Missile for the First Time Against Iran |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-29/us-seeks-to-deploy-hypersonic-for-the-first-time-against-iran|website=Bloomberg News |access-date=2026-04-30}}</ref>

